Yes, a slashed zero (Ø) can be set as a font-variant in CSS, assuming that the font being used supports it as a variant. In CSS, the property used to set a font variant is `font-variant`. 

To use a slashed zero as a font variant, the following code can be used:

```
p {
  font-variant: slashed-zero;
  font-family: Arial;
}
```

In this example, the `font-variant` property is set to `slashed-zero` to specify the use of a slashed zero. The `Arial` font is used as an example here, but other fonts that support a slashed zero variant can be used as well. 

Please note that support for a slashed zero font variant may be limited, so it's a good idea to test the rendered output across different devices and browsers.
